\begin{thm}(Curtis) \label{cut}
The Curtis algorithm ends after finitely many steps when $X_*$ is finite dimensional. Moreover, let $Y_*$ be the graded vector space generated by those untagged items on the $L_i$'s. Denote by $C_*$ the subspace of cycles in $X_*$. There is an algorithm which constructs a map $Y_i\rightarrow C_i$ and a map $C_i\rightarrow Y_i$ which induce an isomorphism between $Y_*$ and the homology of $X_*$.
\end{thm}
\begin{proof}
See \cite{Tan}.
\end{proof}

\begin{cor} \label{unq}
The Curtis table is unique for a finite dimensional complex $X_*$ with ordered basis. In fact, it is specified in the following way:

Let $l(x)$ denote the leading term of $x$.

If there is a tag $a\leftarrow b$, then $a$ is the minimal element of the set $\{l(d(x))|l(x)=b\}$.

If an item $a$ is untagged, then it is the leading term of an element with lowest leading term in a homology class.
\end{cor}
\begin{proof}
See \cite{Tan}.
\end{proof}

